08286nam a22010455i 9780231551922DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20212021nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2020026142  a97802315519227 a10.7312/boll196982doi  a(DE-B1597)566352  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aK3253 7aLAN0080002bisacsh04a341.4/83322300aRegardless of Frontiers :bGlobal Freedom of Expression in a Troubled World /ced. by Agnes Callamard, Lee Bollinger. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tFreedom of Expression and Three Concepts of the Global -- tPART I: A Global Threshold -- t1. Global Norms on Media Regulation -- t2. The Right of Access to Information Held by Public Authorities -- t3. The Protection of Political Expression -- t4. International, Regional, and National Approaches to the Protection of Reputation and Freedom of Expression -- t5. Is There a Global Norm for the Protection of Journalists’ Sources? -- tPART II: Intergovernmental Institutions and International Actors as Norm Entrepreneurs -- t6. The Norm Entrepreneurship of the United Nations -- t7. On “Balancing” and “Social Watchdogs” -- t8. The Role of the Inter- American Human Rights System in the Emergence and Development of Global Norms on Freedom of Expression -- t9. The African Human Rights System -- t10. Globalizing the Battle Against Impunity -- tPART III: Conflicts, Competition, Antiglobalization -- t11. Norms in Conflict -- t12. Making Choices -- t13. China, Information Technology, and Global Freedom of Expression -- t14. The Rise of Global Counternorms -- tPART IV: Interactive Global Jurisprudence -- t15. New York Times Co. v. Sullivan -- t16. Handyside v. the United Kingdom -- t17. Claude Reyes et al. v. Chile: A Global Trailblazer -- t18. Lohé Issa Konaté v. Burkina Faso -- t19. Fast, Far, and Deep -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe United Nations’ Universal Declaration of Human Rights in 1948 proclaimed a vision of freedom of expression exercised regardless of frontiers. Nonetheless, laws and norms regarding the freedom or limits of expression are typically established and understood at the national level. In today’s interconnected world, where newfound threats to free expression have suddenly arisen, how can this fundamental right be secured at a global level?This volume brings together leading experts from a variety of fields to critically evaluate the extent to which global norms on freedom of expression and information have been established and which actors and institutions have contributed to their diffusion. The authors also consider ongoing and new challenges to these norms, from conflicts over hate speech and the rise of populism to authoritarian governments, as well as the profound disruption introduced by the internet. Together, the essays lay the groundwork for an international legal doctrine on global freedom of expression that considers issues such as access to government-held information, media diversity, and political speech. As the world risks renouncing previous commitments to the freedom of expression, Regardless of Frontiers serves as a timely reminder of just how much is at stake and what needs protecting.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aFreedom of expression. 0aFreedom of speech. 0aSovereignty. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Journalism.2bisacsh1 aAnite, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArsène, Séverine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArun, Chinmayi, e